---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Header from '../../components/Header.astro';
---

<BaseLayout 
  title="Blog | Springfield Lot Striping - Parking Lot Maintenance Guides"
  description="Expert guides on parking lot striping costs, ADA requirements in Missouri, restriping frequency, and commercial parking lot maintenance best practices.">
  <Header />
  <div class="pt-28 pb-20 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6">
      <h1 class="text-5xl font-bold text-primary-dark text-center mb-6">Springfield Lot Striping Blog</h1>
      <p class="text-center text-xl text-concrete mb-16">Practical guides and industry insights for commercial property managers in Springfield and Greene County, Missouri.</p>
      
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
        <a href="/blog/parking-lot-striping-cost-springfield-mo/" class="block group">
          <div class="bg-surface rounded-2xl overflow-hidden">
            <img src="/images/xai_grok-imagine-image_20260623_181041_4a336043.jpg" class="w-full h-52 object-cover" alt="Cost guide">
            <div class="p-8">
              <div class="text-brand-yellow text-sm font-medium mb-3">COST GUIDE • JUNE 2026</div>
              <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold group-hover:text-brand-yellow transition-colors">How Much Does Parking Lot Striping Cost in Springfield, MO? (2026 Guide)</h3>
              <p class="text-concrete mt-4 line-clamp-3">Complete breakdown of current pricing for restriping, ADA packages, and new layouts in the Springfield area.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </a>
        
        <a href="/blog/ada-parking-lot-requirements-missouri/" class="block group">
          <div class="bg-surface rounded-2xl overflow-hidden">
            <img src="/images/xai_grok-imagine-image_20260623_181048_c9c83262.jpg" class="w-full h-52 object-cover" alt="ADA guide">
            <div class="p-8">
              <div class="text-brand-yellow text-sm font-medium mb-3">COMPLIANCE • JUNE 2026</div>
              <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold group-hover:text-brand-yellow transition-colors">ADA Parking Lot Requirements in Missouri: What Every Property Owner Must Know</h3>
              <p class="text-concrete mt-4 line-clamp-3">Federal and state rules, stall count tables, fine risks, and how to avoid costly violations.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

<section class="mt-16 space-y-8 text-concrete leading-relaxed">
  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-primary-dark">Use this blog as a practical local maintenance resource</h2>
  <p>The Springfield Lot Striping blog is meant to answer the real questions commercial property managers ask before they schedule a project. That means pricing questions, ADA questions, maintenance timing, and practical concerns about how striping affects the daily operation of a property. This is not a general marketing blog. It is a local resource for people managing commercial spaces in Springfield and surrounding Greene County communities.</p>
  <p>When the site publishes new guides, they should do one of three things: help a property manager estimate cost, clarify a compliance issue, or explain how to maintain a safer lot over time. That approach supports search intent and makes the blog useful for visitors who need quick answers before they call or request a quote.</p>
  <div class="bg-surface rounded-3xl p-8 border border-black/5">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-primary-dark mb-4">What you will find here</h2>
    <ul class="space-y-3 list-disc pl-6">
      <li>pricing breakdowns for restriping, ADA updates, and new layouts</li>
      <li>guides to common Missouri parking lot compliance questions</li>
      <li>maintenance advice for preserving line visibility longer</li>
      <li>commercial planning notes for Springfield-area property managers</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <p>As the blog grows, each new post should support the service pages instead of repeating them. That means more detailed explanations, more examples, and a stronger connection to local property realities. The blog is where the site can answer educational searches while still helping users move toward a quote request when they are ready.</p>
</section>

<section class="mt-12 space-y-6 text-concrete leading-relaxed">
  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-primary-dark">How to use these guides</h2>
  <p>Start with the pricing and ADA posts if you are planning a project for this year. Then use the maintenance guides to decide whether you need a restripe, a layout correction, or a longer-term maintenance plan. The goal is to make the blog useful as a decision tool, not just a content archive.</p>
  <p>If a post raises a question about your specific lot, the next step is a site assessment. Striping decisions are almost always better when they are based on an actual measured property rather than a general rule of thumb.</p>
</section>

<section class="mt-12 space-y-6 text-concrete leading-relaxed">
  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-primary-dark">What we will publish next</h2>
  <p>Future posts should continue the same pattern: useful, local, and specific. That means answering questions about restriping cycles, ADA planning, parking lot pricing, surface prep, and seasonal maintenance in the Springfield market. Those topics are the ones that help property managers move from research to action.</p>
</section>

<section class="mt-12 space-y-6 text-concrete leading-relaxed">
  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-primary-dark">A note on future topics</h2>
  <p>As the blog grows, we may also cover maintenance timing, repaving considerations, common inspection issues, and the tradeoffs between spot refreshes and full layout resets. Those are the subjects that tend to help owners make better decisions and avoid unnecessary cost.</p>
</section>

<section class="mt-12 space-y-6 text-concrete leading-relaxed">
  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-primary-dark">Use the blog to plan before you spend</h2>
  <p>The posts here should help you decide whether you need a quote now or whether a property can wait for a maintenance window. That kind of planning is often the difference between a clean seasonal update and a rushed emergency project.</p>
</section>
</BaseLayout>
